        <div class="col-lg-5 col-md-6 col-sm-6" style="text-align:justify">

          <p>I am an Associate Professor in UMass Amherst's <a href="https://www.cics.umass.edu/">Manning College of Information and Computer Sciences</a>, where I am a member of the <a href="https://groups.cs.umass.edu/theory/">Theory Group</a>. </p>
			  
			  <p>I study algorithms, working at the intersection of theoretical computer science, numerical linear algebra, and machine learning. My group's research is supported in part by an NSF CAREER Award and a Google Research Scholar Award. 
				 <!-- I am especially interested in randomized methods that adapt to streaming and distributed computation. I am also interested in understanding randomized computation and algorithmic robustness by studying computational processes in biological systems.</p>-->
				  

					  
					  <p>I completed my Ph.D. in the <a href="http://toc.csail.mit.edu/">Theory of Computation Group</a> at MIT, advised by <a href="http://people.csail.mit.edu/lynch/">Nancy Lynch</a>. Before MIT, I studied Computer Science and Applied Math at Yale.</p>
			
            <p>Here are my <a href="https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=EeYGZCwAAAAJ&hl=en">Google Scholar profile</a>, <a href="./personal_site/pdfs/cnmusco_cv.pdf">CV</a>, and <a href="https://github.com/cnmusco">GitHub</a>.
			  </p>
			  
			<!--</p>The website for our reading group on distributed computation in biological systems can be found <a href="./realisticReadingGroup/index.html">here</a>.</p>-->
